Date: Wed, 10 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Channel 36 Austin, TX [edited]
<http://www.kxan.com/Global/story.asp?S=3327321&nav=0s3dZhYd>

Whooping cough cases increasing
-------------------------------
There have been 58 confirmed cases of whooping cough in Travis County
schools in 2005. 100 more are suspected. "In 2004, we had 300 cases
reported in to us in the whole year, and we've already had more than 50
percent of that number reported to us, just in the last 6 weeks," Dr Adolfo
Valadez, of the Travis County Health Department, said.
Whooping cough looks like a regular cold or influenza in the beginning, but
gradually gets worse, becoming especially dangerous for children with
asthma. The coughing can become so severe it can close off [airways],
especially tiny ones. But doctors say those shots wear off when kids get a
little older. The greatest danger is when school-age kids catch what looks
like a cold and bring it home to their baby brother or sister. "When you
see that adolescent or adult with a cough history, test for pertussis
because we can treat it," Valadez said.
A 6 week old baby died in 2003 from whooping cough.
******
[3]
Date: Fri, 6 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source Fort Madison Daily Democrat (IA) [edited]
<http://www.dailydem.com/articles/2005/05/06/news/news1.txt>

Area whooping cough numbers climb
----------------------------------
It's been determined to be an outbreak, with 17 confirmed cases of whooping
cough in Lee County since mid-April 2005. Of the 17 cases, 16 are in the
Central Lee Community School District.
Central Lee superintendent Chuck Reighard said the school has responded to
the outbreak by determining who had close contact with the infected student
and then making contact with the families of those who may have been
exposed to urge seeking treatment with the family doctor. Reighard said
that now that the Lee County Health Department has become involved, the
school will determine close contacts, and the health department will take
on the role of contacting families.
Reighard said the majority of the 16 cases at Central Lee are among
students in the middle school, although he said there have been a few at
the elementary and high school levels.
This isn't the 1st time that whooping cough has hit the area. This past
winter, 2004-2005, several confirmed cases were reported among students in
the Fort Madison Community School District. Lee County Health Department
Executive Director Julie Schilling said the department had 31 confirmed
cases of whooping cough from Nov 2004 through Jan 2005, with the majority
of those cases in the Fort Madison Public School system.
A release of information concerning the outbreak from the Lee County Health
Department did not indicate that there were incidents of whooping cough in
Fort Madison this time. Schilling said whooping cough has been in Iowa
since last summer [2004] but usually shows up in the fall. "But it can
occur at any time," Schilling said.
